The binary search algorithm works by repeatedly dividing the search interval in half until the target element is either found or the interval is empty. In each iteration, the middle element of the current search range is checked against the target value. Depending on whether the target is less than, greater than, or equal to the middle element, the search continues in the left or right half of the current range. This process repeats until the target is found or the search interval becomes empty.

